spanGrp.span: ‘There was a cat at the window, looking at a bird with his binoculars;
Jirö michi dul michi dul bentana ska dú sũã' binokulo wa
then the bird also saw him with the binoculars.
tara dú të í sũẽ-gẽ ĩã binokulo wa
There the cat wanted to devour the bird,
Jeska ra michi jenã (m) dú kata-gle-wã
but the cat’s hand could not reach it.
tara michi ka jula dö í ska
So, the cat thought about going in through the door.
ta michi të í begetsá mĩ-wã jũ jũkö kenẽga
The cat ran fast and went through the door.
Michi tunã' bue kawãu jukö kenẽga
But the owner was there and so hit him bang!
tara í wagi kalu të í tiá ¡pá
It threw him down into the litter outside.
Tsáu-mĩ jũ (m) shebega jirö (m) basurero nã
Then the cat came and sat to figure out how it could grab it.
Ñerö michi beteũ-nẽ jẽk káwã í begetsö (_) mẽnẽbi í guge-mĩ-wã-ite
It thought for a while and went up on the wall.
ñerö michi të í begetsá tã'ĩ ñerö (_) michi kagõu pe pared ktömẽ
He was down in front of the bird, waved his hand back and forth just like the bird flew in the cage.
diá kalu-nẽ dú wömẽ jula jua-gẽ mẽnẽu dú jũr-gẽ jaula nã bi jamĩgweta_jigweta jamĩgweta_jigweta í jula wa
Then, the bird felt in it.
Ñerö dú wö janã-wã í ska
Then the bird realized and began to figure out how it could escape.
tara dú të begetsá mẽnẽbi í shkömĩu í yiga mẽnẽbi shkömĩu yiga
Then the cat went to grab it, but the bird held the door.
Ñerö (_) michi mẽnẽ gugö-wã ska (_) dú të jukö kugẽ-ka ska
The cat/the bird went inside the house where its owner was.
Michi/ e dú kau-mĩ junã' dö-mĩu í wagi ska
The owner saw the cat and hit it with an umbrella;
Ñerö í wagi të michi sũã' ta michi kbá-ite paragwa wa
she threw him out through the door.
báu-mĩ-ite jamĩ jũkö kenẽga í të
So the cat began to figure out how to catch the bird;
Ñerö michi michi mẽnẽ-nẽ í begetsö mẽnẽbi í të (_) dú guge-wã-ite
There he realized that he could go through the pipe to get to the bird.
ta í wö janã-wã ke jeska tubo jenẽi nã í jẽk pakkö-ka dögãu k/ dú ska
So, he went in, but the bird saw him come through the pipe.
Ñerö í jẽk pakká-wã tara dú të sũã' í dagãu tubo weko nã
So he went and brought what people use to play bowling;
ta mãĩ í mẽnẽu-te pe jinõ-glö boliche
it brought that ball and dropped it down the pipe, so it would hit the cat in the middle;
je bola tsáte-wã bájá-wã-mĩ-ite tubo jenẽi nã döu (hm) mãĩ michi dagãu-te í mõska
and it did hit him bang!
So the cat ate that thing that people use to play and could not catch the bird.
Ñerö michi të je je pe jinõ-glö wa katá-wã tara michi ka ĩã dú klonẽ-wã
The toy took him all the way to the street inside the pipe.
Je jirö/ pe jinõ-glö të menetse-mĩ rö (_) kaye ska tubo jenẽi nã
Now the cat cannot stand up anymore; it rolled down and down and ended up in a play ground.’
